      Private markets are the new public markets
   =20
 =20

You could just imagine letting=C2=A0companies=C2=A0precisely customize how =
their stock trades:
=09Your stock can trade 24 hours a day, or just regular trading hours, or o=
ne auction a day, or one big liquidity event per quarter, or only on specif=
ic dates that you choose at your discretion.=09The trading price of your st=
ock could be publicly reported in real time, or with a delay, or not at all=
.=09You can disclose news and audited GAAP financial statements=C2=A0public=
ly to everyone, or only to your current investors, or you can keep everythi=
ng=C2=A0secret.=09You can let anyone buy your stock, or only =E2=80=9Caccre=
dited investors=E2=80=9D (roughly people making over $200,000 a year), or o=
nly institutional investors, or only US investors, or only non-US investors=
.=09Or you can blacklist particular investors, or categories of investors: =
no activist funds, maybe, or no high-frequency traders,=C2=A0or no environm=
ental, social and governance funds, or nobody who owns shares in your compe=
titors.=09You can give yourself various rights to step into trades: You can=
 have a right of first refusal over any sales of stock, or you get to appro=
ve each trade, or you can allow them only at particular prices, etc.=09You =
can allow short selling, or not.=09You can give your outside shareholders e=
qual voting rights, or keep super-voting shares for your founder and inside=
rs, or not give the public shareholders any votes at all.

Etc. In current US public markets, most of these choices are made for you=
=C2=A0(respectively: regular-ish hours, public prices, disclose financials =
to everyone, anyone can buy, no blacklists, no messing with trades, yes sho=
rting
  [6]
), though voting rights are pretty customizable. But in private markets, th=
e field is wide open: There are some restrictions on letting non-accredited=
 investors buy your stock, and you=E2=80=99ll probably feel better if you p=
rovide financial information to potential investors. But at this point accr=
edited investors (and institutions) are a large chunk of the investor class=
, so it=E2=80=99s not like that=C2=A0is cutting you off from a ton of money=
.
The nice thing about public markets is that everyone is there; they are a p=
owerful=C2=A0coordination mechanism. Every US public stock trades on pretty=
 much all the stock exchanges, the exchanges are all interlinked nicely, an=
d in practice there just is =E2=80=9Cthe public stock market=E2=80=9D where=
 all the investors and all the public companies go. So if your stock trades=
 on the public market, everyone will be able to buy it. Whereas if I came t=
o you pitching Matt=E2=80=99s Private Market, where auctions happen once a =
week and you get to blacklist shareholders, you will naturally ask me quest=
ions like =E2=80=9Cwhat institutional investors trade on your market,=E2=80=
=9D while those investors will ask me questions like =E2=80=9Cwhat companie=
s have listed on your market,=E2=80=9D and if the answer to both questions =
is =E2=80=9Cnobody yet=E2=80=9D then it will stay that way. If there are to=
o many options, then none of them will concentrate liquidity and create a d=
eep two-sided market.
Still a fun dream would be to create a General Private Market that gives co=
mpanies a big menu of all of these choices. Sign up all the institutional i=
nvestors, saying, =E2=80=9Clook, whatever market structure any particular c=
ompany wants, we will give it to them, and you=E2=80=99ll be able to access=
 all of them from the same website.=E2=80=9D (At this point the institution=
al investors all seem to be resigned to signing up for a new trading=C2=A0p=
latform every few months anyway, so it can=E2=80=99t be that hard to onboar=
d them for one more.) And then that market offers continuous 24-hour tradin=
g in some stocks and weekly auctions in others, and every mutual fund can t=
rade all of the stocks in whatever format the company wants, except of cour=
se the stocks where they=E2=80=99re blacklisted.
I=E2=80=99m going to get like six emails from people saying =E2=80=9Cyou ar=
e not familiar with my company, but actually we have built that market.=E2=
=80=9D
In this extremely general world, would companies go public? On the one hand=
, the public markets would still probably be a better coordination mechanis=
m than the private ones: Everyone, including non-accredited investors, can =
go there, and the uniform rules that all default to more trading =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0continuous trading, short selling, no blacklists, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0would still make them much more liquid and attractive to traders than th=
e customizable rules of the private market.
But=C2=A0chief executive officers grouse=C2=A0constantly=C2=A0about various=
 features of public markets they don=E2=80=99t like =E2=80=94=C2=A0the cost=
s of disclosure, the class-action lawsuits,
  [7]
=C2=A0the activists, the short sellers, the high-frequency traders for some=
 reason =E2=80=94=C2=A0and a market that was like =E2=80=9Cyou can have mos=
t of the features of public markets that you like, but you can choose which=
 ones to turn off=E2=80=9D would have some appeal. And if most of the inves=
tor class would sign up for it =E2=80=94=C2=A0and they would, if you got a =
couple of hot startups to list =E2=80=94=C2=A0then maybe the prices and liq=
uidity would be good=C2=A0enough.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t know, every story about private markets is some variant on =
either =E2=80=9Cprivate-company investors are desperate to find ways to sel=
l, but won=E2=80=99t go public because the prices for=C2=A0initial public o=
fferings are too low,=E2=80=9D which is weird (
why would the private market prices be=C2=A0higher?),=C2=A0or else =E2=80=
=9Ceveryone wants to buy shares of this hot hot startup, but it won=E2=80=
=99t let them.=E2=80=9D There is not a single solution to those problems, b=
ut there is a high-level solution of the form =E2=80=9Cmaximize the liquidi=
ty of your stock, subject to your preferences about when=C2=A0to minimize i=
ts liquidity.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Anyway Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Bailey Lipschultz, Swetha Gopinath=C2=A0and=
