<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the first few months of 2023, on its way in=
to bankruptcy, Bed Bath &amp; Beyond Inc. sold a ton of stock. In January 2=
023, it had about 117.3 million shares outstanding, worth about $3.35 each;=
 by April, it had 739.1 million, worth about $0.30 each. Then it went bankr=
upt and now=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
5325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly9zZWVraW5nYWxwaGEuY29tL2FydGljbGUvNDYxODcwMi1iZWQt=
YmF0aC1iZXlvbmQtZmlsZWQtYmFua3J1cHRjeS1wbGFuLXdpcGVzLW91dC1zaGFyZWhvbGRlcnM=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7635d273" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the shares are worth zero</a>, =
though you can find <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjMtMTAtMzEvYmFkLXBhc3N3b3Jkcy1hcmUtc2VjdXJpdGllcy1mcmF1ZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQw=
NTA5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ=
1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB1e1dcedc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">contrarian views</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These stock sales always struck me as extraord=
inarily cynical: Bed Bath pretty much knew that it would be filing for bank=
ruptcy with no recovery for shareholders, but it went out and raised a few =
hundred million dollars from meme-stock retail investors to hand directly t=
o creditors. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325=
192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMt=
MDQtMjQvYmVkLWJhdGgtbW92ZXMtaW50by10aGUtYmV5b25kP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDkyNF9NT05=
FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPT=
I0MDUwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0efa55c7"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">I wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bed Bath was kind of like =E2=80=
=9Chey everyone, we went bust, sorry, but our lenders are such nice people =
and they could really use a break, we=E2=80=99re gonna pass the hat and it =
would be great if you could throw in a few hundred million dollars to make =
them feel better.=E2=80=9D And the retail shareholders did! With more or le=
ss complete disclosure, they bought 622 million shares of a stock that (1) =
was pretty clearly going to be worthless and (2) now is worthless,=C2=A0so =
that Bed Bath could have more money to give to its lenders when it inevitab=
ly liquidated.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wild times. But the=C2=A0<em>way=C2=A0</em>tha=
t Bed Bath did a lot (not all) of this stock selling was also interesting. =
Eventually Bed Bath <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjMtMDMtMzAvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLWhhcy1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLXRvLXNlbGw_Y21waWQ9=
QkJEMDUwOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR=
0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNTA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB3d12cc8c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">did a normal stock offering</a>, but before that,=
 it did an odd structured deal with Hudson Bay Capital Management LP.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXNvbGQtc29tZS1zdG9jaz9jbXBp=
ZD1CQkQwNTA5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2x=
ldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBa0475fe9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">talked</a> about the <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDgvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLWdvdC1pd=
HMtZGVhbC1kb25lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDkyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwm=
dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDUwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXl=
zdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBed91e572" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">deal</a> at the time. Ba=
sically Hudson Bay paid Bed Bath $225 million up front, and Bed Bath agreed=
 to deliver Hudson Bay some stock, over time, whenever Hudson Bay asked for=
 it. At each delivery, Hudson Bay would get the stock at a discount to the =
current trading price. So intuitively it would get a little stock, it would=
 sell it, it would come back for a little more stock, etc. Each time, it wo=
uld sell the stock for more than the (discounted) price it paid for it, so =
it would make money. The stock would go down over time, but that wasn=E2=80=
=99t Hudson Bay=E2=80=99s problem: It kept getting new batches of=C2=A0stoc=
k at a discount to whatever the price happened to be.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, Hudson Bay could re-up the trade eight m=
ore times, at $100 million each time, if the stock stayed above an agreed p=
rice. Ultimately Bed Bath raised about $360 million from Hudson Bay, and so=
ld it about 311 million shares of stock. Based on the average prices over t=
he period, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3532519=
2.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMD=
MtMzAvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLWhhcy1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLXRvLXNlbGw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwO=
TI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRt=
X3Rlcm09MjQwNTA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC3=
d12cc8c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">I guessed</a> that Hudson Bay made about $84 million from =
the deal, which is a pretty chunky commission on a $360 million capital rai=
se.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s how I <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXNvbGQtc2=
9tZS1zdG9jaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCa0475fe9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">originally characterized the=
 trade</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What Bed Bath has done here, I thi=
nk, is that it has=C2=A0<em>sold the right to do meme-stock offerings=C2=A0=
</em>to some institutional investors. The investors get the ability to pick=
 their spots to sell stock, and can get the stock at a discount from Bed Ba=
th.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One oddity here is that, when Bed Bath agreed =
to this trade, it had about 117 million shares outstanding, and it ultimate=
ly sold 311 million new shares to Hudson Bay. If it had done that all at on=
ce, Hudson Bay would have owned about 73% of the stock. But it didn=E2=80=
=99t, and that would have been crazy. Hudson Bay was not a long-term fundam=
ental investor in Bed Bath; it didn=E2=80=99t want to own a majority of the=
 stock. It wanted to get a little stock, sell it for a profit, get a little=
 more stock, sell it for a profit, and repeat as long as that kept working.=
 I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325192.257342=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMzAvYm=
VkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLWhhcy1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLXRvLXNlbGw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwOTI0X01PT=
kVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09=
MjQwNTA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD3d12cc8c"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">wrote at the time</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hudson Bay has bought roughly 73% =
of Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock, 311 million out of its 428 million shares outs=
tanding=C2=A0US securities law requires investors to disclose their share o=
wnership =E2=80=94 on Schedule 13D or 13G =E2=80=94 within 10 days after th=
ey get above 5% of a company=E2=80=99s stock. Hudson Bay has never filed a =
13D for Bed Bath; it doesn=E2=80=99t even show up on Bloomberg=E2=80=99s ho=
lders list. Hudson Bay may have bought almost 311 million Bed Bath shares, =
but it didn=E2=80=99t keep them for long; it was selling them as fast as it=
 could get them.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The disclosure isn=E2=80=99t the main point, t=
hough. US securities laws have what are called =E2=80=9Cshort-swing profit =
rules=E2=80=9D: If you own more than 10% of a company=E2=80=99s stock, you =
sort of aren=E2=80=99t allowed to=C2=A0<em>trade=C2=A0</em>it. The rule is =
found in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325192.=
257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc4cA/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB647cdd14" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Section 16(b) of the Exchange Act</a>=
, and=C2=A0it is nominally a rule against insider trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
e theory is that if you=E2=80=99re a big shareholder you might have inside =
information =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it doesn=E2=80=99t actually require any proo=
f of using inside information. Instead, the basic mechanism is that if you=
=E2=80=99re a 10% holder, and you buy more stock, and then you=C2=A0<em>sel=
l=C2=A0</em>the stock within six months of buying it for more than you paid=
 for it, you=E2=80=99re not allowed to keep the profits. The company can su=
e you to get the profits back, or, if the company doesn=E2=80=99t want to s=
ue you (because you=E2=80=99re a big insider shareholder), <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuam=
RzdXByYS5jb20vbGVnYWxuZXdzL3NldHRsaW5nLXNlY3Rpb24tMTYtYi1zaG9ydC1zd2luZy0yN=
jU0MDY0Lw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfdc64065" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a shareholder can brin=
g the case</a>. In practice there are entrepreneurial lawyers who bring the=
se cases and get the attorneys=E2=80=99 fees from settlements.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can see how those lawyers would be intrigu=
ed here. The simple form of this story is something like =E2=80=9CHudson Ba=
y became a 73% shareholder of Bed Bath &amp; Beyond, and then for months it=
 would buy a little bit of Bed Bath stock and turn around and sell it at a =
profit,=C2=A0to the tune of $360 million of stock and probably at least ten=
s of millions of dollars of profits.=E2=80=9D That story is a gold mine for=
 lawyers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, that simple story is not quite right. Eve=
ryone knows about these rules, and there are standard solutions. Hudson Bay=
 did not just=C2=A0<em>get=C2=A0</em>73% of Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock. Inste=
ad what happened is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It bought some=C2=A0<em>convertible pr=
eferred stock</em>, plus warrants to buy more convertible preferred.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The convertible preferred stock contai=
ned the terms of the deal: Hudson Bay could convert=C2=A0its preferred shar=
es, a little bit at a time, into common shares at a discount to the trading=
 price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But there was a limit on H=
udson Bay=E2=80=99s right to convert: It=C2=A0was only allowed to convert a=
ny of its preferred stock if, after the conversion, it would own 9.99% or l=
ess of Bed Bath=E2=80=99s common stock. This limit is commonly called a =E2=
=80=9CSection 16 blocker.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>This was fine because, again, it was converting and selling a little bit a=
t a time; it didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to get a huge block of =
stock at once. The Section 16 blocker was there for Hudson Bay=E2=80=99s co=
nvenience: It allowed Hudson Bay to say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re not a 10% ho=
lder, so we=E2=80=99re not subject to the Section 16 rules.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Technically Section 16 covers not just ownersh=
ip of common stock but also ownership of options or securities that can be =
converted into common stock.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So=C2=A0owning preferred stock that could be converted into 73% o=
f the common stock would count as being a 73% owner.<a class=3D"footnote-in=
dex" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; disp=
lay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But Hudson Bay=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t </em>own preferred stock t=
hat could be converted into 73% of the common stock: It could only ever be =
converted into 9.99% of the stock=C2=A0<em>at a time</em>. The Section 16 b=
locker, in theory, is supposed to protect it from becoming a 10% holder.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does it work? Man, I don=E2=80=99t know; what =
I=E2=80=99ll tell you is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This has always seemed=C2=A0kind of li=
ke arcane metaphysics to me.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I use=
d to be an equity derivatives structurer and we all sure believed that Sect=
ion 16 blockers worked. Certainly a lot of deals work this way.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Miles Weiss and Eli=
za Ronalds-Hannon <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQ=
tMDUtMDkvZm9ybWVyLWJlZC1iYXRoLXN1ZXMtaHVkc29uLWJheS1mb3ItMzAwLW1pbGxpb24tdH=
JhZGluZy1nYWlucz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJ=
nV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5=
c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9213d57d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">report today</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The former=C2=A0Bed Bath &amp; Beyond Inc., se=
eking to generate cash for its creditors, sued to recover more than $300 mi=
llion in trading profits from=C2=A0Hudson Bay Capital Management, the hedge=
 fund at the center of a last-ditch financing plan that failed to prevent t=
he retailer=E2=80=99s collapse.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The former retailer filed a lawsuit last week =
claiming that, behind the scenes, Hudson Bay orchestrated the terms for a F=
ebruary 2023 offering so it could acquire a huge, cut-rate stake in Bed Bat=
h without having to disclose the ownership under=C2=A0a little-known rule=
=C2=A0for corporate insiders.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVu=
dHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3J4SVdlOFBpZHJYOC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B38212f72" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">the complaint</a>,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#f=
ootnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: non=
e !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-blo=
ck;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and I guess the main point here is that if you are a bankrupt com=
pany and you=E2=80=99ve got a shot at clawing back $300 million=C2=A0to han=
d over to your creditors, you have to give it a try. The theory of the comp=
laint is that Hudson Bay was a 10% shareholder, the Section 16 blocker didn=
=E2=80=99t work, and so it should have to give back all of its profits on t=
he trade:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This beneficial ownership =E2=80=9Cblocker=E2=
=80=9D was illusory. It was drafted by the Hudson Bay Defendants and solely=
 for their benefit. BBBY had no way to enforce the blockers in the derivati=
ve securities, and it had an incentive not to enforce them. Policing the bl=
ockers meant self-policing by the Hudson Bay Defendants, who routinely unde=
rcounted their beneficial ownership of BBBY=E2=80=99s common stock in contr=
avention of SEC rules.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The blockers=E2=80=99 deficiencies were laid b=
are in the first days of the financing, when the Hudson Bay Defendants, rel=
ying on flawed and self-serving beneficial ownership calculations, repeated=
ly tore through the 9.99% cap.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is true that Bed Bath had no particular rea=
son to enforce the blocker. The point of the blocker is just to be able to =
say =E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t have the right to get 10% of the stock, so we=
=E2=80=99re not a 10% holder.=E2=80=9D Though I can see how, if you end up =
buying 73% of the stock and dumping it, you might <em>look like=C2=A0</em>t=
he sort of 10% holder that the rules were meant to capture? <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDUtMDkvZm9ybWVyLWJlZC1iYXRoLXN1=
ZXMtaHVkc29uLWJheS1mb3ItMzAwLW1pbGxpb24tdHJhZGluZy1nYWlucz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA=
5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG=
1fdGVybT0yNDA1MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC=
9213d57d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">Hudson Bay disagrees</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hudson Bay, which managed about $20 billion at=
 year-end, said in a statement that Bed Bath creditors were behind the laws=
uit, and that the hedge fund never owned more than 10% of the retailer=E2=
=80=99s shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt is sad that creditors seeking to d=
istract from their significant financial losses have resorted to filing fac=
tually flawed and baseless claims in a desperate attempt to extract an undu=
e payment,=E2=80=9D a Hudson Bay spokesperson said in the statement.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The complaint also gives a timeline of Hudson =
Bay=E2=80=99s conversions and sales. On March 20, 2023, for instance, Hudso=
n Bay converted $23.6 million of its preferred stock into 30.3 million shar=
es of common stock=C2=A0at a conversion price of $0.7777 per share. The sto=
ck closed that day at $0.8125; the volume-weighted average price was $0.841=
4,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tra=
nsparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and about 86.4 million shares traded that day.=C2=A0If Hudson Bay=
 got $0.84 per share for its sales, then it made about $1.9 million on the =
day. In all, =E2=80=9Cin the 52 trading days between February 7 and the Apr=
il 23 bankruptcy petition date, the Hudson Bay Defendants submitted a total=
 of 90 conversion or exercise requests to BBBY.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The complaint calculates that Hudson Bay made =
$310 million of profits, though the details are redacted, and=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cprofits=E2=80=9D under Section 16 is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGlua2VkaW4uY29tL3B1b=
HNlL3NlY3Rpb24tMTZiLXRyYWRpbmctdHJhcC11bndhcnktaW5zaWRlci1jcmFpZy1zY2hlZXIv=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB639ad404" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a weird calculation</a> that do=
es not reflect=C2=A0economic reality;=C2=A0I suspect my $84 million guess i=
s closer to the real number.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, what an amazing trade. There Bed Bath w=
as, more or less bankrupt, trying to round up money for creditors. Hudson B=
ay came to it with a deal that, ultimately, did raise $360 million from ret=
ail investors to hand to creditors, and Bed Bath paid Hudson Bay probably t=
ens of millions of dollars for its help. And now it might be able to extrac=
t $300 million more from Hudson Bay to hand over to creditors!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The general rule of stocks is that, if you are=
 a shareholder in a public company, you can lose all your money, but you ca=
n=E2=80=99t lose <em>more</em> than=C2=A0that. If you buy stock and the com=
pany goes bankrupt and there=E2=80=99s not enough money to pay the creditor=
s, you get $0 back, but you don=E2=80=99t have to chip in=C2=A0<em>more=C2=
=A0</em>money to pay the creditors. With its Hudson Bay trade, Bed Bath fou=
nd a way to get around that rule. Twice! First, in the lead-up to bankruptc=
y,=C2=A0it raised money from=C2=A0shareholders to hand directly to creditor=
s, and now, in bankruptcy, it is going back to Hudson Bay for more.</p>
