0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">accr=
edited investors</a>=E2=80=9D (roughly people making over $200,000 a year),=
 or only institutional investors, or only US investors, or only non-US inve=
stors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or you can blacklist partic=
ular investors, or categories of investors: no activist funds, maybe, or no=
 high-frequency traders,=C2=A0or no environmental, social and governance fu=
nds, or nobody who owns shares in your competitors.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">You can give yourself various rights to step into trades:=
 You can have a right of first refusal over any sales of stock, or you get =
to approve each trade, or you can allow them only at particular prices, etc=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can allow short selling, or =
not.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can give your outside sha=
reholders equal voting rights, or keep super-voting shares for your founder=
 and insiders, or not give the public shareholders any votes at all.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Etc. In current US public markets, most of the=
se choices are made for you=C2=A0(respectively: regular-ish hours, public p=
rices, disclose financials to everyone, anyone can buy, no blacklists, no m=
essing with trades, yes shorting<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>), though voting rights are pretty customizable. But in private markets=
, the field is wide open: There are some restrictions on letting non-accred=
ited investors buy your stock, and you=E2=80=99ll probably feel better if y=
ou provide financial information to potential investors. But <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325192.257342/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
c2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9yZXZpZXctZGVmaW5pdGlvbi1hY2NyZWRpdGVkLWludmVzdG9yLTIwMjM=
ucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d83285e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">at this point</a> accred=
ited investors (and institutions) are a large chunk of the investor class, =
so it=E2=80=99s not like that=C2=A0is cutting you off from a ton of money.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The nice thing about public markets is that ev=
eryone is there; they are a powerful=C2=A0coordination mechanism. Every US =
public stock trades on pretty much all the stock exchanges, the exchanges a=
re all interlinked nicely, and in practice there just is =E2=80=9Cthe publi=
c stock market=E2=80=9D where all the investors and all the public companie=
s go. So if your stock trades on the public market, everyone will be able t=
o buy it. Whereas if I came to you pitching Matt=E2=80=99s Private Market, =
where auctions happen once a week and you get to blacklist shareholders, yo=
u will naturally ask me questions like =E2=80=9Cwhat institutional investor=
s trade on your market,=E2=80=9D while those investors will ask me question=
s like =E2=80=9Cwhat companies have listed on your market,=E2=80=9D and if =
the answer to both questions is =E2=80=9Cnobody yet=E2=80=9D then it will s=
tay that way. If there are too many options, then none of them will concent=
rate liquidity and create a deep two-sided market.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still a fun dream would be to create a General=
 Private Market that gives companies a big menu of all of these choices. Si=
gn up all the institutional investors, saying, =E2=80=9Clook, whatever mark=
et structure any particular company wants, we will give it to them, and you=
=E2=80=99ll be able to access all of them from the same website.=E2=80=9D (=
At this point the institutional investors all seem to be resigned to signin=
g up for a new trading=C2=A0platform every few months anyway, so it can=E2=
=80=99t be that hard to onboard them for one more.) And then that market of=
fers continuous 24-hour trading in some stocks and weekly auctions in other=
s, and every mutual fund can trade all of the stocks in whatever format the=
 company wants, except of course the stocks where they=E2=80=99re blacklist=
ed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=E2=80=99m going to get like six emails from =
people saying =E2=80=9Cyou are not familiar with my company, but actually w=
e have built that market.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In this extremely general world, would compani=
es go public? On the one hand, the public markets would still probably be a=
 better coordination mechanism than the private ones: Everyone, including n=
on-accredited investors, can go there, and the uniform rules that all defau=
lt to<em> more trading</em> =E2=80=94=C2=A0continuous trading, short sellin=
g, no blacklists, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0would still make them much more liqui=
d and attractive to traders than the customizable rules of the private mark=
et.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0chief executive officers grouse=C2=A0=
<em>constantly=C2=A0</em>about various features of public markets they don=
=E2=80=99t like =E2=80=94=C2=A0the costs of disclosure, the class-action la=
wsuits,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0the activists, the short sellers, the high-frequency traders for =
some reason =E2=80=94=C2=A0and a market that was like =E2=80=9Cyou can have=
 most of the features of public markets that you like, but you can choose w=
hich ones to turn off=E2=80=9D would have some appeal. And if most of the i=
nvestor class would sign up for it =E2=80=94=C2=A0and they would, if you go=
t a couple of hot startups to list =E2=80=94=C2=A0then maybe the prices and=
 liquidity would be good=C2=A0<em>enough</em>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, every story about privat=
e markets is some variant on either =E2=80=9Cprivate-company investors are =
desperate to find ways to sell, but won=E2=80=99t go public because the pri=
ces for=C2=A0initial public offerings are too low,=E2=80=9D which is weird =
(<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35325192.257342/a=
